I notice that both the old and new versions don't work well in concurrent scenario, but the new version is more obviously to be discovered:
    
```java
    int next;
    do {
      next = this.value.incrementAndGet(); // <-- here is the point, it always increment the `value`
      if (next > endValue && this.value.compareAndSet(next, startValue)) {
        return endValue;
      }
    } while (next > endValue);    
```
    
in the case of `org.apache.skywalking.apm.commons.datacarrier.buffer.Buffer`, it may leave some "black holes" in the queue.
though the class `AtomicRangeInteger` is only used in `org.apache.skywalking.apm.commons.datacarrier.buffer.Buffer`, and it handles the `null` values carefully, once the `AtomicRangeInteger` is used in other more scenarios, it may be a bug somehow, I am not sure whether this is possible to happen.
    
> Bellow is the test codes, which doesn't necessary always print 5000, sometimes are much less than 5000:

```java
    @Test
    public void testConcurrency() throws InterruptedException {
        int count = 10000;
        final AtomicRangeInteger integer = new AtomicRangeInteger(0, count);
        final CountDownLatch latch = new CountDownLatch(1);
        final CountDownLatch mainLatch = new CountDownLatch(count);
        final Map<Integer, Boolean> seen = new ConcurrentHashMap<Integer, Boolean>();
        final ExecutorService executor = Executors.newCachedThreadPool();
        for (int i = 0; i < count; i++) {
            executor.submit(new Runnable() {
                @Override public void run() {
                    try {
                        latch.await();
                        int i = integer.getAndIncrement();
                        seen.put(i, Boolean.TRUE);
                        mainLatch.countDown();
                    } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                        e.printStackTrace();
                    }
                }
            });
        }
        latch.countDown();
        mainLatch.await();
        System.out.println("seen.size() = " + seen.size());
        executor.shutdown();
    }
```

@kezhenxu94 
you should use a thread-safe set
`final Set<Integer> seen = Collections.synchronizedSet(new HashSet<Integer>());`
